ng transgressions such as riots, prostitution, theft, and murder and at the same time tracing how the state controlled and punished its unruly population. Taking us through the city's streets, workshops, and houses, she gives voice to ordinary people—the man accused of stealing, the woman accused of prostitution, and the vagabond expelled from the city. She finds that Istanbul in this period remains mischaracterized—in part by the sensational and exotic accounts of European travelers who portrayed it as the embodiment of Ottoman decline, rife with decadence, sin, and disease. Linking the history of crime and punishment to the dramatic political, economic, and social transformations that occurred in the eighteenth century, Zarinebaf finds in fact that Istanbul had much more in common with other emerging modern cities in Europe, and even in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCrimezTurkeyzIstanbulxHistory. 0aPunishmentzTurkeyzIstanbulxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  a18th century.  acivic.  acrime historians.  acrime history.  acrime.  acriminals.  acriminology.  aearly modern history.  aeconomic history.  agovernment and governing.  ahistorians.  ahistorical analysis.  aistanbul.  amediterranean.  amiddle east scholars.  amiddle east.  amulticultural society.  amurder.  anonfiction.  apolitical history.  aprostitution.  aretrospective.  arevisionist history.  ariots.  asocial change.  asocial sciences.  atheft.  atransgressions.  aturkey.  aturkish society.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026220140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094756640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520947566423Coveruhttps